AU  - McAfee, R. Preston
T1  - Externalities and Asymmetric Information*
PY  - 1991
Y1  - 1991/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/2937908
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 106
IS  - 1
SP  - 103
EP  - 121
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - A reconsideration of the Pigovian theory of regulating externalities via taxation is undertaken for environments with private information. The presence of private information may have no effect on the social optimum; but when it has an impact, it is to cause a group of different agents to share the same production or consumption levels. The model developed provides an appealing characterization of when such situations transpire: they occur when the individuals who desire most to engage in some activity are the ones who society least wants to participate. Since such instances could potentially be regulated by the imposition of quantity controls, this may explain authorities' apparent predilection for quantity limits rather than tax-cum-subsidy schemes to manage many externalities.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2937908
ER  - 



